04567nam a22005655i 9780822384205DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20022002ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223842057 a10.1515/97808223842052doi  a(DE-B1597)554445  a(OCoLC)1058438308  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aDS556.5 ǂb P45 2002 7aHIS0480002bisacsh04a959.704/41 aPelley, Patricia M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPostcolonial Vietnam :bNew Histories of the National Past /cPatricia M. Pelley; ed. by Masao Miyoshi, Harry Harootunian, Rey Chow. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (340 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aA John Hope Franklin Center Book : 3200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Diacritics -- tIntroduction: Postcolonial Visions -- t1 Constructing History -- t2 The Land of the Việt and Việt Nam -- t3 National Essence and the Family-State -- t4 Chronotypes, Commemoration: A New Sense of Time -- tEpilogue -- tList of Abbreviations -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNew nations require new histories of their struggles for nationhood. Postcolonial Vietnam takes us back to the 1950s to see how official Vietnamese historians and others rethought what counted as history, what producing history entailed, and who should be included as participants and agents in the story. Beginning with government-appointed historians’ first publications in 1954 and following their efforts over the next thirty years, Patricia M. Pelley surveys this daunting process and, in doing so, opens a wide window on the historical forces and tensions that have gone into shaping the new nation of Vietnam.Although she considers a variety of sources—government directives, census reports, statistics, poetry, civic festivities, ethnographies, and museum displays—Pelley focuses primarily on the work of official historians in Hanoi who argued about and tried to stabilize the meaning of topics ranging from prehistory to the Vietnam War. She looks at their strained and idiosyncratic attempts to plot the Vietnamese past according to Marxist and Stalinist paradigms and their ultimate abandonment of such models. She explores their struggle to redefine Vietnam in multiethnic terms and to normalize the idea of the family-state. Centering on the conversation that began in 1954 among historians in North Vietnam, her work identifies a threefold process of creating the new history: constituting historiographical issues, resolving problems of interpretation and narration, and conventionalizing various elements of the national narrative. As she tracks the processes that shaped the history of postcolonial Vietnam, Pelley dismantles numerous clichés of contemporary Vietnamese history and helps us to understand why and how its history-writing evolved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aHISTORY / Asia / Southeast Asia.2bisacsh1 aChow, Rey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarootunian, Harry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMiyoshi, Masao, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822384205zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822384205423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822384205/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyt